# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ambuyat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ambuyat/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:ambuyat/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:ambuyat/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:ambuyat/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:ambuyat/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:ambuyat/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:ambuyat/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:ambuyat/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:ambuyat/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:ambuyat/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:ambuyat/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:ambuyat/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:ambuyat/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:ambuyat/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:ambuyat/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:ambuyat/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:ambuyat/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:ambuyat/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:ambuyat/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:ambuyat/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:ambuyat/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:ambuyat/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] Traditionally, an ice shaving machine is used to churn out the shaved ice used in the dessert, originally hand cranked but now more often motorised.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] Many Southeast Asian coffee shops, hawker centres and food courts sell this dessert.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] Early versions of ais kacang was first known to have been prepared around the time before and after the First World War, where the costs of ice manufacturing was becoming more affordable.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] An earlier variant of the Singaporean dish was described as green, made from shaved ice, paired with syrups, *soaked seeds* and seaweed jelly and was sold mainly by street vendors.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] The dish underwent many different alterations and variants throughout the history of Singapore, where during the 1920s, one version of it was described as shaved ice topped with rose water, lime or liquorice.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] A version of the dish, known as Kachang mera, was also sold during the 1930s.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] By the 1940s, the version of the dish described as having "shaved ice heaped into a little mountain", topped with red beans, "a Chinese grape-like fruit", syrup, and condensed or evaporated milk, similar to how it is being prepared today, began to appear.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] Some earlier variants of ais kacang are no longer sold, such as the ice ball version of the dessert, which was popular during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] In Malaysia, variants now contain a large serving of *attap chee* (palm seed), red beans, sweet corn, grass jelly, roasted peanuts, and cubes of agar agar as common ingredients.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] Other less common ingredients include aloe vera, *cendol*, *nata de coco*, and ice cream.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] A final topping of evaporated milk, condensed milk, or coconut milk is drizzled over the mountain of ice along with red rose syrup and sarsi syrup.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] Some stalls have even introduced novelty toppings such as durian and chocolate syrup.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] There are also versions that shun the multi-coloured syrup and are served instead with just a drizzling of palm sugar syrup.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] In Singapore, traditional ice kachang is usually made from shaved ice, packed into a mountain-like shape and consists of red beans, creamed corn, attap chee, cendol, and grass jelly, similar to the Malaysian version, and drizzled with syrups made from gula melaka, red rose syrup, and pandan syrup.
[src:ambuyat/ais-kacang] The dish has evolved to include fruits such as durian, mango, toppings such as Milo, peanuts, and sago pearls among others.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Based on a report released by International Organisation of Good Templars in 2016, Malaysia has the third highest tax on alcohol worldwide at 15%, behind Norway and Singapore which are predicted to keep increasing.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] The country has an annual spending of RM2 billion on alcoholic drinks.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Prior to the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Malaysia together with Vietnam plans to drop import tariffs on beer, whisky, and other alcoholic drinks.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] The tradition of brewing alcoholic drinks in Malaysia is most prominent in the island of Borneo.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Indigenous islanders traditionally drank home-made rice wine called tuak and tapai in their communal gatherings and harvest festivals of Gawai Dayak and Kaamatan.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol consumption in the Malay Peninsula has been less common since the introduction of Islam.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, the production and consumption of alcohol (*arak*) has been a tradition since the time of Hang Tuah in the 15th century.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 20th century, palm toddy was popular among the local Indian and Chinese communities.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] The British brought their own traditional brewed alcoholic drinks, such as beer and stout.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 1930, the first brewery was established in neighbouring British Singapore.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since the British colonial times, Tiger Beer was the first commercial beer brewed in 1932 by Malayan Breweries Limited, a Singapore-based brewery which was formed from a merger between Heineken and Fraser and Neave (F&N).
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] The beginning of alcohol production in Malaysia started in 1968, when two leading breweries, Guinness and Malayan, merged to form a new company known as Guinness Anchor Berhad.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 1970, Carlsberg established its first brewery outside Kuala Lumpur in Shah Alam.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Both are since the only legal commercial breweries in Malaysia, which account for 95% of the total beer and stout volume in the country market.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2007, another two breweries known as Napex and Jaz brewed beer for pubs in the country, but both have since ceased from operation.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Beside local productions, many alcoholic drinks in the country are also imported from neighbouring countries such as Singapore, Thailand, Indonesia, Philippines and Vietnam.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] The legal drinking age (purchasing) for Malaysia is 21 years old and above.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since 2020, the legal limit for blood alcohol level while driving in Malaysia is 50 mg per 100 ml for blood test; 22 μg per 100 ml for breath test; and 67 mg per 100 ml for urine test.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Public drinking or public intoxication is not a crime in Malaysia, unless the drunken person caused "annoyance" towards others or exhibit "disorderly behaviour", which may be punished with a RM20 to RM25 fine or a 10 to 14 days jail under the Penal Code or Minor Offences Act 1955.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, these laws are rarely enforced.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Any vendors, restaurants and retailers need a licence to serve or sell tap/draft beers, liquor and spirits in the country.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Bottled and canned beers are exempted from such licence requirements, which is why it is common to find many vendors and coffee houses serving alcohol in their premises without a licence.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Malaysia also imposes nationwide regulations for vendors to place their alcoholic drinks into separate refrigerators or storage places, although this was opposed by certain vendors in the state of Penang.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] The high tax on alcohol has increased the price of alcoholic drinks in Malaysia, harming some drinkers who turn to unsafe alcohol smuggled in from neighbouring countries.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2018, around 45 people died in the country's worst methanol poisoning involving foreign workers and several Malaysians due to the consumption of cheap fake liquors acquired from the country's black markets.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Following Demerit Points System for Traffic Offences (KEJARA), a police officer or JPJ officer can take breath, blood or urine samples of drunk driver.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] If alcohol content is found in the samples, a fine of RM 2000 or 6 months' imprisonment may be imposed for the first offence.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is generally prohibited for Muslim consumers in the country as Malaysia's sharia law forbids Muslims from drinking alcohol.
[src:ambuyat/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is mostly banned for Muslims in the states of Kelantan and Terengganu.
[src:ambuyat/ambuyat] In the past, it was a dietary staple for the indigenous people of the region.
[src:ambuyat/ambuyat] In parts of Eastern Indonesia, there is a similar dish called papeda, which is usually served with stir-fried water spinach (*kangkung*), papaya flower buds, and a turmeric-tinged fish curry called *kuah ikan kuning*, flavoured with green chillies, lemongrass, and bay leaves.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] The origin of American fried rice has a number of tales, anecdotes, urban legend, and related stories.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] Most of those stories are related to either American troops or their culture.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] This hypothesis is based on deconstructing the composition of the dish, combined with tracing the cooking techniques used in the American fried rice in order to trace the cooking lineage of this dish in the United States (Chuenwattana 2020).
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] All of the cooking techniques and ingredients using in the American Fried Rice are similar to the dish called "Mexican rice" in Southern United States or Cajun's dirty rice in Louisiana, Mexican rice cooked or fried rice grains with tomatoes or ketchup.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] Mexican rice often served with variety of dishes (e.g. fried eggs, fried chicken, crispy bacon).
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] Mexican rice recipe for the first time appeared on a daily menu recipe in the Newark Evening Star and Newark Advertiser on June 2nd, 1910.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] According to this recipe, Mexican rice is accompanied with frankfurter.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] However, Mexican rice was paired with several other dishes after that.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] Mexican rice or Cajun rice is presumed to be in Thailand via the American soldiers who stationed here during the Cold War.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] Both Mexican rice or Cajun rice would eventually become the ancestor of the American fried rice in Thailand.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] American fried rice in Malaysia and Southern Thailand have different versions that have been modified from the original version.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] Usually it replaces the side dish of "bacon" or "ham" with Thai red meat (Malay: *daging masak merah ala Thai*).
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] This change was made because Thai Malays and Malaysian Malays practice Islam.
[src:ambuyat/american-fried-rice] This dish is sometimes confused with the Malaysian dish called nasi goreng USA, in which the initialism “USA” stands for shrimp (udang), squid (sotong) and chicken (ayam).
[src:ambuyat/amplang] The shape and size of amplang might vary, from traditional elongated "tiger nails" to dice or ping-pong balls.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] The colour may range from yellow to light brown.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] In Indonesia, amplang is traditionally associated with Samarinda, the capital city of East Kalimantan, since the amplang cracker home industry has thrived in the city since the 1970s.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Traditionally, amplang was made from *ikan pipih* or *ikan belida* (*Chitala lopis*).
[src:ambuyat/amplang] However, since this freshwater fish had become scarce, amplang makers replaced them with *ikan tenggiri* (wahoo) or *gabus* (striped snakehead).
[src:ambuyat/amplang] From Samarinda, the popularity of this savoury fish cracker spread to other cities in the Borneo island, such as Balikpapan, Banjarmasin, Pontianak, and even to Sabah in Malaysia.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Amplang is often sought as *oleh-oleh* (foodstuff gift or souvenir) by those who visited East Kalimantan.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Today, amplang made by home industries in Kalimantan has been widely distributed, available in marketplaces and supermarkets in Indonesian cities, such as Jakarta, Bandung, Surabaya, and Medan.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Amplang is commonly produced by home industries in Samarinda, East Kalimantan in Indonesia.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Other than Samarinda, amplang production centres also can be found in Balikpapan, Pontianak in West Kalimantan and Banjarmasin in South Kalimantan.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] In neighbouring Malaysia, amplang is mainly produced on the east coast of Sabah, particularly in the town of Tawau.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Today, the makers of amplang in East Kalimantan produce the snack not only with a fish flavor, but in a variety of flavors such as crab and seaweed.
[src:ambuyat/amplang] Nevertheless, the original amplang kuku macan remains the most popular.
